"script": "What if you got thirsty and tried to drink the sea? The first gulp tastes sharp and salty, and you swallow anyway. But seawater is far saltier than your blood. So to flush out all that salt, your body has to pee out even more water than you drank. Then thirst hits harder, not softer. Drink more, and you only speed up the loss. Your cells start shriveling as water gets pulled out of them to dilute the salt. In the end, surrounded by an entire ocean, you'd die of dehydration, drier than if you'd drunk nothing at all.",
